p54o.text:
(1) The Office shall grant authorization to an association upon the association's request, provided that it:

- a) has its registered office in the territory of the Czech Republic;

- b) has an established supervisory board;

- c) the members of its statutory body and supervisory board are of good repute;

- d) at least 1 member of the statutory body and 1 member of the supervisory board have at least 3 years of experience in operating or managing unmanned systems;

- e) persons who will provide training to association members operating unmanned systems and participants in international events have at least 3 years of experience in operating or managing unmanned systems; and

- f) has an internal organizational structure, internal control system, and rules that ensure the safe operation and management of unmanned systems with regard to:

- 1. the protection of life, health, property, and privacy of persons, the protection of civil aviation against unlawful acts, and the protection of the environment;

- 2. the fulfillment of conditions stipulated by a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the operation of unmanned aircraft^39), from which the applicant does not intend to deviate; and

- 3. the fulfillment of obligations specified in paragraph 5.

(2) In addition to the general requirements for submissions under the Administrative Procedure Code, the application must define the conditions stipulated by a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the operation of unmanned aircraft^39) from which the applicant intends to deviate, and the conditions that will apply instead. The application for granting authorization to an association must be accompanied by:

- a) a document, not older than 3 months, proving the fulfillment of the good repute condition for a member of the statutory body or supervisory board, if the person is a citizen of another state, issued by the state of which that person is a citizen, or an affidavit if that state does not issue such a document; for a citizen of another European Union member state, this document may be replaced by an extract from the Criminal Register with an appendix containing information recorded in the criminal records of another European Union member state; and

- b) documents proving the fulfillment of the conditions specified in paragraph 1, letters d) to f).

(3) For the purposes of proceedings concerning an application for granting authorization to an association, a natural person is considered to be of good repute if they have not been finally convicted of an intentional criminal offense, nor have they been finally convicted of a criminal offense committed through negligence in connection with the operation or management of an unmanned system, unless they are deemed not to have been convicted. For the purpose of verifying good repute, the Office shall request an extract from the Criminal Register. The request for an extract and the extract from the Criminal Register shall be submitted electronically in a manner allowing remote access. For the purpose of verifying good repute, the Office is also authorized to request a certified copy of a final decision from the court. If the decision does not contain facts relevant for verifying good repute, the Office is authorized to inspect those parts of the criminal file that contain such facts.

(4) The authorized association shall adjust the rules ensuring the safe operation and management of unmanned systems from the perspectives listed in paragraph 1, letter f), so that they are in accordance with the conditions stipulated in the association's authorization. Until the association's rules are adjusted, a member of the authorized association, the authorized association, or a participant in an international event may not operate or manage an unmanned system.

(5) The authorized association shall:

- a) publish, in a manner allowing remote access, the rules ensuring the safe operation and management of unmanned systems from the perspectives listed in paragraph 1, letter f), as adjusted pursuant to paragraph 4 (hereinafter referred to as the “association's rules”);

- b) demonstrably acquaint its members and participants in international events who intend to operate or manage an unmanned system with the association's rules;

- c) ensure that its members operating unmanned systems and participants in international events complete training to acquire the theoretical knowledge, and where applicable, practical skills, necessary for managing an unmanned system to the extent and in the manner stipulated in the association's authorization, and after completing this training, issue these members with an identification card for an association member operating an unmanned system;

- d) maintain a list of its members operating or managing an unmanned system and participants in international events, and continuously update this list;

- e) supervise the operation and management of unmanned systems and take corrective measures if a violation of the association's rules is detected;

- f) refrain from engaging in business or other gainful activity as its primary activity;

- g) demonstrably and without undue delay notify a person who was an association member operating or managing an unmanned system of the fact that their membership in the association has ceased;

- h) comply with the association's rules if it is the operator of an unmanned system; and

- i) must have liability insurance for damages from the operation of an unmanned system and have paid the premium with a minimum limit of insurance coverage stipulated by the association's rules or a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the insurance of air carriers and aircraft operators^10a), if it is the operator of an unmanned system.

(6) The authorized association shall notify the Office of any change in the facts on the basis of which the association's authorization was granted, within 15 days from the date on which it occurred, and simultaneously submit documents proving this change. The Office shall amend the decision on granting the association's authorization if it concerns a fact stated in this decision and if the conditions for granting the association's authorization continue to be met to the extent of the notified change.

(7) The Office shall revoke the association's authorization if the authorized association has requested it. If the authorized association ceases to meet the conditions for granting the association's authorization or has seriously violated an obligation stipulated by this Act or a condition stipulated in the association's authorization, the Office shall restrict or revoke the association's authorization according to the nature and extent of the detected deficiencies. The restriction of the association's authorization shall be carried out by restricting the purpose or method of operating unmanned systems or by restricting a part of the Czech Republic's airspace that may be used for flying unmanned aircraft.

(8) If the Office grants the authorized association's request for a new association authorization, the existing association authorization shall cease on the day the decision granting this request becomes final.

(9) The Office shall publish, in a manner allowing remote access, decisions on:

- a) granting authorization to an association;

- b) amending a decision on granting authorization to an association; or

- c) restricting or revoking authorization to an association.

p83.text:
(1) The authorized person shall

- a) issue or revoke certificates to legal and natural persons engaged in the business of manufacturing sport flying equipment and related products, aircraft parts and equipment, repairs and maintenance, and monitor their compliance with obligations;

- b) prepare and submit to the Ministry of Transport proposals for operational and technical regulations for the operation of sport flying equipment and proposals for training curricula for their approval, and after approval by the Ministry of Transport, issue these regulations and training curricula;

- c) supervise the activities of builders of sport flying equipment;

- d) approve, recognize, and verify the airworthiness of sport flying equipment and issue, extend, and revoke their airworthiness certificates;

- e) maintain a register of sport flying equipment pursuant to § 84b and assign identification marks to designated sport flying equipment;

- f) grant qualifications to pilots and other persons involved in the operation of sport flying equipment, issue pilot licenses, record qualifications therein, extend their validity, issue certificates attesting to achieved qualifications, and maintain records thereof;

- g) issue or revoke consent for the operation of training centers for pilots of individual types of sport flying equipment, and monitor their compliance with obligations;

- h) determine conditions for the use of areas for take-offs and landings of sport flying equipment, register these areas, approve operational regulations and the suitability of registered areas; submit records of these areas to the Ministry of Transport for publication;

- i) authorize the performance of test flights of sport flying equipment;

- j) grant consent for organizing public air displays of sport flying equipment;

- k) supervise the activities of operators, pilots, and other persons involved in the operation of sport flying equipment;

- l) provide necessary cooperation to state administration bodies in connection with the investigation of aviation accidents and incidents involving sport flying equipment;

- m) appoint and dismiss operations inspectors and technical inspectors; submit a list of appointed and dismissed operations inspectors and technical inspectors to the Ministry of Transport for publication.

(2) In the interest of aviation safety or other public interest, the authorized person or the Office may, in justified cases, restrict or prohibit the flight of certain sport flying equipment.

p84a.text:
(1) Operations inspectors and technical inspectors are, within the scope of supervision over sport flying equipment, authorized to

- a) demand the submission of documents necessary for the operation of sport flying equipment;

- b) impound the technical certificate of sport flying equipment if a defect in the airworthiness of the sport flying equipment is found, until the defect in airworthiness is rectified;

- c) prohibit a flight if it would endanger the safety of air traffic, the life, health, or property of persons, or the environment, or any other legally protected interest;

- d) impound a pilot's license or other certificate attesting to qualification and order a verification of professional competence or a re-examination of the medical fitness of the holder of the impounded license if, during the performance of activities related to the operation of sport flying equipment, deficiencies are exhibited that may endanger the safety of air traffic;

- e) revoke the pilot's license of a person who has endangered the safety of air traffic, violated flight rules, or rules for the operation of sport flying equipment, and hand it over without undue delay to the authorized person for further proceedings.

(2) Technical inspectors are further, within the scope of supervision over the construction, manufacture, and repairs of sport flying equipment and related products, aircraft parts and equipment, authorized to

- a) demand the submission of all documents related to the construction and manufacture of sport flying equipment and related products, aircraft parts and equipment, especially all calculations, construction and manufacturing documentation, and the construction logbook;

- b) enter premises where sport flying equipment and related products, aircraft parts and equipment are being constructed or manufactured, inspect machinery and tools, verify materials and connecting components used;

- c) in the event of identified design defects, request or impose the performance of strength, elasticity, and other tests; in the event of manufacturing, prohibit the operation of previously manufactured sport flying equipment, or request design changes or the preparation of an expert opinion.

p84b.text:
(1) Sport flying equipment defined in § 81 para. 2 letters a) to g) shall be entered in the register of sport flying equipment (hereinafter referred to as the „register“) based on a written request from the owner or operator with the owner's consent, under the following conditions:

- a) the owner or operator of the sport flying equipment is a natural person with permanent residence in the Czech Republic or a legal person with its registered office in the Czech Republic;

- b) the sport flying equipment is not registered in another state;

- c) the airworthiness of the sport flying equipment has been verified, or is being verified pursuant to § 83 para. 1 letter d), or its airworthiness certificate issued by a foreign state authority has been recognized as valid.

(2) An identification mark shall be assigned to sport flying equipment entered in the register. By assigning the identification mark, the sport flying equipment acquires the nationality of the Czech Republic.

(3) The data to be entered in the register, the data that can be published from it, and the method of marking sport flying equipment shall be stipulated by an implementing legal regulation.

p92.text:
(1) A natural person commits an administrative offense by:

- a) failing to provide the requested data to the Office upon request, in contravention of § 12a (4);

- b) using products, aircraft parts or equipment, or aeronautical ground equipment in civil aviation without a valid certificate, in contravention of § 16 (1);

- c) performing the duties of aeronautical personnel without a valid competency certificate, in contravention of § 18 (3);

- d) performing the duties of aeronautical personnel despite knowing about an illness or changes in health status that limit or preclude the performance of such duties, in contravention of § 19 (4);

- e) operating equipment or carrying out activities in the protected zone of an aeronautical structure without the consent of the Office, in contravention of § 40;

- f) constructing a building or facility outside protected zones in contravention of § 41 (1);

- g) placing a building or facility outside protected zones in contravention of § 41 (1);

- h) failing to comply with an order of the aircraft commander, in contravention of § 54;

- i) operating a public air display without consent, in contravention of § 78;

- j) using a sport flying device for profit, in contravention of § 81 (1);

- k) operating a sport flying device without a valid pilot's license, in contravention of § 84c (1);

- l) failing to comply with an order issued by the Ministry of Transport pursuant to § 88 (5) or disobeying a prohibition issued by the Office pursuant to § 89 (2) (o) point 6 for the preservation of civil aviation safety;

- m) failing to comply with an order issued by an airport operator, an air navigation service provider, an air carrier, or an operator of aerial work or aerial activities for own use, issued for the fulfillment of their tasks;

- n) operating commercial air transport without a license or permit, operating aerial work or aerial activities for own use without a permit, or operating an airport without a permit; or

- n) endangering flight safety by damaging an aeronautical structure or other equipment that is part of such structure, or disrupting the operation of aeronautical ground equipment.

(2) A natural person commits an administrative offense by:

- a) as an aircraft operator registered in the aircraft register, an aircraft owner, a pledgee, or a person to whom an entry in the aircraft register pertains, failing to promptly report or substantiate to the Office all changes to data recorded in the aircraft register, in contravention of § 6;

- b) as an aircraft operator, a sport flying device operator, or a coded device operator, using an aircraft address in contravention of § 17c (1);

- c) as a consultant, failing to maintain confidentiality, in contravention of § 55a (3);

- d) as an aircraft operator, aircraft pilot, or air navigation service provider, failing to report without undue delay to the Institute an incident other than a serious incident, in contravention of § 55b (1);

- e) as an aircraft operator or sport flying device operator, failing to maintain airworthiness or failing to subject the aircraft or sport flying device to regular airworthiness checks;

- f) as an aircraft operator, operating an aircraft without liability insurance for damages caused by its operation; or

- g) as a sport flying device operator, operating a sport flying device without liability insurance for damages caused by its operation.

(3) A natural person commits an administrative offense by:

- a) in contravention of directly applicable European Union regulations governing airport slot allocation^25), intentionally and repeatedly using a coordinated airport at a time that differs substantially from the slot allocated by the coordinator, or using an allocated slot in a manner substantially different from that specified by the coordinator, thereby disrupting air traffic or airport operations;

- b) conducting flights in the airspace of the Czech Republic in contravention of the conditions stipulated in this Act or directly applicable European Union regulations governing the conduct of flights in airspace^26);

- c) endangering flight safety by violating aviation regulations or directly applicable European Union regulations governing the conduct of flights in airspace^26);

- d) causing an accident in air traffic during the operation of an aircraft or sport flying device by violating an obligation stipulated by this Act or directly applicable European Union regulations governing the conduct of flights in airspace^26);

- e) in contravention of directly applicable European Union regulations governing the investigation of accidents and incidents in civil aviation^19):

- 1. making available or using records obtained during the investigation of an aircraft accident or serious incident for purposes other than their investigation or the improvement of aviation operational safety,

- 2. as a person involved in an accident or serious incident, failing to promptly notify the Institute that an accident or serious incident has occurred,

- 3. failing to inform the Institute within the stipulated period about measures taken based on its safety recommendation, or

- 4. failing to implement appropriate procedures when implementing measures adopted following a safety recommendation issued by the Institute; or

- f) in contravention of directly applicable European Union regulations governing the reporting of occurrences in civil aviation^37):

- 1. as a person obliged to report an occurrence, failing to report such occurrence or failing to report it within the stipulated period or in the stipulated manner, or

- 2. as an involved person, using information provided from the European central repository.

(4) A fine may be imposed for an administrative offense:

- a) up to CZK 100,000, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (a) or paragraph 2 (a);

- b) up to CZK 300,000, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (g), (j) or (l), paragraph 2 (c) or (d), or paragraph 3 (e) point 1, 2 or 3 or (f);

- c) up to CZK 500,000, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (c) to (f), (i) or (n), paragraph 2 (b) or (g), or paragraph 3 (a);

- d) from CZK 50,000 to CZK 1,000,000, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (b) or (h), paragraph 2 (e) or (f), or paragraph 3 (b), (c) or paragraph (e) point 4; or

- e) from CZK 100,000 to CZK 5,000,000, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (k) or (m) or paragraph 3 (d).

(5) A prohibition of activity may be imposed for an administrative offense:

- a) up to 6 months, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (d), paragraph 2 (e) or (f);

- b) up to 1 year, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (b), (c), (i) or (j), or paragraph 3 (b) or (c); or

- c) up to 2 years, if it is an offense under paragraph 1 (k), or paragraph 3 (d).

p93a.text:
(1) A legal entity or a natural person carrying out business activities commits an administrative offense by failing to:

- a) carry out professional training in accordance with § 85x (1) of the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the protection of civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference^23) without a permit;

- b) carry out professional training of dog handlers and dogs intended for the detection of explosives in accordance with § 85z (1) without a permit or carries it out in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27);

- c) notify, in conflict with § 86c (2), that it intends to carry out the activity of a “known consignor”, a “known supplier of in-flight supplies” or a “known supplier of airport supplies” within the stipulated period, or, in conflict with § 86c (3), fails to inform the Office of a change in the facts stated in the notification; or

- d) disclose, in conflict with § 86d (4), a fact contained in a decision by which basic measures were stipulated.

(2) A legal entity or a natural person carrying out business activities commits an administrative offense by, as a/an:

- a) airport operator,

- 1. operating an airport in conflict with § 85m (1) without an approved airport security program;

- 2. failing to notify the Office of other changes to the security program in conflict with § 85m (3);

- 3. failing to ensure the implementation of measures and procedures specified in the airport security program in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the protection of civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference^23); or

- 4. failing to fulfil any of the obligations under § 85n (1) or (2), or fulfilling such an obligation in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27);

- b) airport operator or air carrier,

- 1. failing to ensure the performance of detection screening of passengers, cabin baggage and hold baggage in conflict with § 85p (1);

- 2. failing to ensure subsequent protection of passengers, cabin baggage and hold baggage in conflict with § 85q;

- 3. failing to adopt extraordinary measures, change extraordinary measures, notify the adoption, change or cancellation of extraordinary measures, or failing to fulfil an obligation arising from an extraordinary measure ordered by the Office in conflict with § 86f; or

- 4. issuing an airport identification card or entry permit, or failing to withdraw an airport identification card or entry permit, in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27);

- c) person carrying out detection or security screening, carrying out such screening in conflict with § 85d, or carrying it out in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27);

- d) air carrier,

- 1. failing to ensure that information on aircraft security search is kept on board the aircraft in conflict with § 85o; or

- 2. failing to ensure the secure escort and storage of an item for which consent to bring it in has been granted, in the airport area or on board the aircraft, in conflict with § 85p (5);

- e) air navigation service provider, failing to draw up or adhere to a security program in conflict with § 85r, or failing to make it available at the request of the Office;

- f) “regulated agent”, entrusting a natural or legal person with the performance of security screening in connection with cargo and mail outside its premises in conflict with § 85s (1);

- g) person entrusted by a “regulated agent” with the performance of security screening in connection with cargo and mail,

- 1. carrying out such security screening in conflict with § 85s (2) without the consent of the Office or carrying it out in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27); or

- 2. failing to immediately notify a change in facts affecting the granting of consent in conflict with § 85s (4);

- h) employer of a natural person who is to perform work activities stipulated by the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the protection of civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference^23), failing to ensure, in conflict with § 85w, that these work activities are performed by natural persons who have successfully completed professional training;

- i) person ensuring the performance of detection screening,

- 1. allowing the use of a dog intended for the detection of explosives in conflict with § 86a, without the person performing the duties of a dog handler having been issued a permit to perform this activity; or

- 2. ensuring the performance of detection screening in a different manner than that stipulated by the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the protection of civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference^23), without a permit or in conflict with the conditions stipulated therein, in conflict with § 86b (1);

- j) recipient of basic measures,

- 1. failing to comply with the basic measures stipulated under § 86d (1);

- 2. failing to inform about facts significant for assessing the content and scope of the performance of its activity in conflict with § 86d (3); or

- 3. carrying out an activity directly related to the stipulated basic measures before the day of enforceability of the decision on their stipulation in conflict with § 86d (5);

- k) person who is obliged to apply aviation security standards against acts of unlawful interference according to the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the protection of civil aviation against acts of unlawful interference^23), failing to draw up or update a security program, failing to ensure the implementation of measures and procedures stipulated therein, or failing to submit the security program at the request of the Office;

- l) “regulated agent”, “known consignor”, “approved supplier of in-flight supplies”, trainer or carrier of cargo or mail subjected to security screening, carrying out this activity in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27) without the approval of the Office;

- m) “known consignor”, “known supplier of in-flight supplies”, “known supplier of airport supplies” in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27),

- 1. carrying out these activities, even though it has not been designated to carry out this activity; or

- 2. carrying out deliveries of in-flight and airport supplies or handling consignments; or

- n) “regulated agent”, air carrier or airport operator, failing to withdraw the designation as a “known consignor”, “known supplier of in-flight supplies” or “known supplier of airport supplies” in conflict with the directly applicable European Union regulation governing the implementation of detection and security screening^27).

(3) A fine may be imposed for an administrative offense:

- a) up to CZK 500,000, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1 letter c) or paragraph 2 letter c), d) point 1, letter j) point 2 or letter n);

- b) from CZK 50,000 to CZK 1,000,000, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1 letter d) or paragraph 2 letter a) point 2, letter b) point 4, letter d) point 2, letter g) point 2, letter i), letter j) point 1 or 3, letter k) or letter m) point 2;

- c) from CZK 75,000 to CZK 3,000,000, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1 letter a) or b) or paragraph 2 letter a) point 3, letter e), f), letter g) point 1, letter h), l) or letter m) point 1; or

- d) from CZK 100,000 to CZK 5,000,000, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 2 letter a) point 1 or 4 or paragraph 2 letter b) points 1 to 3.

(4) A prohibition of activity for up to 2 years may be imposed for an administrative offense, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 2 letter a) point 4 or paragraph 2 letter b) point 1 or 2.

p93c.text:
(1) A legal entity or a natural person carrying out business activities commits an administrative offense by, in contravention of a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the rights of persons with disabilities and persons with reduced mobility and orientation in air transport^33),

- a) as an air carrier, tour operator or travel agent,

- 1. failing to make publicly available, in a form and languages accessible to passengers, safety rules relating to the carriage of persons with disabilities and persons with reduced mobility and orientation, including rules for restricting the carriage of such persons or the carriage of their mobility equipment due to aircraft size;

- 2. failing to make reasonable efforts to propose an acceptable alternative transport to a person with a disability or a person with reduced mobility and orientation whose reservation has been legitimately refused;

- 3. failing to take all necessary measures at all its points of sale, including sales using means of distance communication, to accept notifications of the need for assistance from persons with disabilities and persons with reduced mobility and orientation, or failing to ensure that accepted notifications are properly and timely forwarded;

- 4. failing to inform, within the specified period or in the specified manner, a person with a disability or a person with reduced mobility and orientation whose reservation has been legitimately refused or who has been refused boarding, of the reasons for such refusal;

- 5. unreasonably refusing a person with a disability or a person with reduced mobility and orientation a flight reservation, or refusing to accept such person on board, even though that person holds a valid ticket and reservation; or

- 6. failing to offer a person who has been denied boarding due to their disability or reduced mobility and orientation, or a person accompanying them, reimbursement of expenses or re-routing;

- b) as an airport operator,

- 1. failing to establish quality standards for assistance to persons with disabilities and persons with reduced mobility and orientation, failing to determine the resources needed to meet them, or failing to publish its quality standards;

- 2. failing to designate arrival and departure points within the airport premises where persons with disabilities or persons with reduced mobility and orientation can easily announce their arrival, failing to provide basic airport information at these points, or failing to clearly mark these points; or

- 3. failing to ensure that a person with a disability or a person with reduced mobility and orientation is provided with free assistance so that they are able to take the flight for which they have a reservation;

- c) as an air carrier or airport operator,

- 1. failing to ensure that all persons used to provide direct assistance to persons with disabilities and persons with reduced mobility and orientation have knowledge of how to meet the specific needs of these persons; or

- 2. failing to ensure that all its employees undergo disability awareness training; or

- 3. failing to ensure training on disability equality and disability awareness for all airport personnel who come into direct contact with the travelling public; or

- d) as an air carrier, failing to provide free assistance to a person with a disability or a person with reduced mobility and orientation upon departure, arrival or transit at the airport.

(2) A legal entity or a natural person carrying out business activities commits an administrative offense by, in contravention of a directly applicable European Union regulation governing information in air transport^34), as a contracting air carrier,

- a) failing to inform the passenger of the identity of the operating air carrier or carriers when making a reservation, or of any change thereto after the reservation has been made;

- b) failing to provide a passenger who has decided not to fly with an air carrier subject to an operating ban with reimbursement of expenses or re-routing; or

- c) failing to define the obligation to inform passengers of the identity of the operating air carrier or carriers in the general terms and conditions of sale relating to the contract of carriage.

(3) A legal entity or a natural person carrying out business activities commits an administrative offense by, in contravention of a directly applicable European Union regulation governing compensation and assistance to passengers in the event of denied boarding, cancellation or significant delay of flights^1g), as an air carrier,

- a) failing to fulfil the information obligation, failing to arrange for flight re-routing or failing to reimburse related expenses, failing to provide care or failing to compensate for damage incurred in connection with denied boarding, flight cancellation or delay; or

- b) as an air carrier, demanding payment of the difference in ticket price or failing to refund it, if the passenger was placed in a higher or lower class than that for which the ticket was purchased, in connection with denied boarding, flight cancellation or delay.

(4) A fine may be imposed for an administrative offense:

- a) up to CZK 300,000, if it is an administrative offense under paragraph 1 letter a) point 1 or 4 or letter c) point 2 or 3, or under paragraph 2 letter a) or c);

- b) up to CZK 500,000, if it is an administrative offense under paragraph 1 letter a) point 2 or 3, letter b) point 1 or 2 or letter c) point 1 or under paragraph 3 letter b); or

- c) from CZK 50,000 to CZK 1,000,000, if it is an administrative offense under paragraph 1 letter a) point 5 or 6, letter b) point 3 or letter d), paragraph 2 letter b) or paragraph 3 letter a).

p93d.text:
(1) A legal entity or a natural person engaged in business commits an administrative offense by, in contravention of a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the operation of unmanned aircraft^39):

- a) operating an unmanned aircraft system in the specific category of operation without an authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems or a declaration of compliance with a standard scenario;

- b) as an unmanned aircraft system operator:

- 1. operating an unmanned aircraft system that does not meet the technical requirements stipulated by this directly applicable regulation, a directly applicable European Union regulation governing unmanned aircraft systems^43), a document certifying authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems, or a light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate;

- 2. failing to ensure that the unmanned aircraft system operated by it is controlled by a pilot who has reached the age of 16 years;

- 3. not being registered in the register of unmanned aircraft system operators;

- 4. failing to display its registration number on the unmanned aircraft;

- 5. failing to report to the Institute, within the stipulated period or in the stipulated manner, a safety-related event concerning the unmanned aircraft system operated by it; or

- 6. failing to fulfill any of the obligations stipulated by this directly applicable regulation, thereby causing an accident;

- c) as an unmanned aircraft system operator in the specific category of operation:

- 1. operating an unmanned aircraft system in contravention of the conditions stipulated by the document certifying authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems or the light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate;

- 2. failing to ensure compliance with operational restrictions stipulated by this directly applicable regulation, a directly applicable European Union regulation governing the conduct of flights in airspace^26), a document certifying authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems, a light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate, or the rules of an association;

- 3. failing to regularly evaluate the adequacy of adopted risk mitigation measures or failing to update them;

- 4. failing to apply for an amendment to the authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems or light unmanned aircraft systems;

- 5. failing to notify the Authority of a change in data contained in the declaration of compliance with a standard scenario;

- 6. failing to maintain its established light unmanned aircraft system operator safety management system;

- 7. failing to update the manual for the light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate or failing to submit such updated manual to the Authority; or

- 8. failing to provide parts of the manual for the light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate to employees; or

- d) as an unmanned aircraft system operator, failing to fulfill another obligation of an unmanned aircraft system operator stipulated by this directly applicable regulation.

(2) A legal entity or a natural person engaged in business commits an administrative offense by, in contravention of a directly applicable European Union regulation governing controlled unmanned aircraft system airspace^40):

- a) providing a common information service or a controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service without authorization;

- b) as a common information service provider or a controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service provider, failing to provide the service to the extent or in the manner prescribed by this directly applicable regulation;

- c) as a controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service provider:

- 1. failing to take measures to coordinate activities with air traffic service providers; or

- 2. failing to notify the Authority of the commencement or termination of providing controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic services; or

- d) as an unmanned aircraft system operator:

- 1. operating an unmanned aircraft system without observing the rules for the use of the airspace of the Czech Republic defined by a general measure issued pursuant to § 44g or without utilizing controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic services provided in the part of the airspace of the Czech Republic defined by this general measure;

- 2. failing to fulfill any of the obligations stipulated by this directly applicable regulation before or during the flight of an unmanned aircraft; or

- 3. failing to adopt measures or procedures for unforeseen situations or failing to make these measures or procedures available to controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service providers.

(3) A legal entity or a natural person engaged in business commits an administrative offense by:

- a) as an unmanned aircraft system operator:

- 1. in contravention of § 54a (5), failing to notify the Authority, within the stipulated period, of a change in data recorded in the register of unmanned aircraft system operators;

- 2. in contravention of § 54c (2) or (3), failing to surrender, within the stipulated period, the document certifying authorization for the operation of unmanned aircraft systems or the light unmanned aircraft system operator certificate;

- 3. in contravention of § 54d or a directly applicable European Union regulation governing insurance for air carriers and aircraft operators^10a), failing to have liability insurance for damages from the operation of an unmanned aircraft system with the minimum stipulated limit of insurance coverage or failing to have paid the insurance premium;

- 4. in contravention of § 54k (1), failing to issue a certificate of competency for controlling an unmanned aircraft system in the specific category of operation or issuing such certificate without the conditions for doing so being met;

- 5. in contravention of § 54k (2), failing to ensure the conduct of training to the stipulated extent, in the stipulated manner, or in cooperation with a person authorized by the Authority;

- 6. in contravention of § 54k (9)(a), failing to send a copy of the certificate of competency for a remote pilot in the specific category of operation issued by it to the Authority within the stipulated period; or

- 7. in contravention of § 54k (9)(b), failing to notify the Authority, within the stipulated period, that a reason for its return has arisen for the holder of the certificate of competency for controlling an unmanned aircraft system in the specific category of operation issued by it;

- b) as an authorized association:

- 1. in contravention of § 54o (4), operating an unmanned aircraft system;

- 2. in contravention of § 54o (5)(a), failing to publish the association's rules;

- 3. in contravention of § 54o (5)(b), failing to familiarize its members or participants in an international event who intend to operate or control an unmanned aircraft system with the association's rules;

- 4. in contravention of § 54o (5)(c), failing to ensure that its members controlling an unmanned aircraft system or participants in an international event complete the stipulated training, or failing to issue to these members, after completing such training, an association member's card for controlling an unmanned aircraft system;

- 5. in contravention of § 54o (5)(d), failing to keep a list of its members operating or controlling an unmanned aircraft system or participants in an international event or failing to continuously update this list;

- 6. in contravention of § 54o (5)(e), failing to supervise the operation and control of unmanned aircraft systems or failing to take corrective measures in the event of detecting a violation of the association's rules;

- 7. in contravention of § 54o (5)(f), failing to refrain from engaging in business or other gainful activity as its main activity;

- 8. in contravention of § 54o (5)(g), failing to notify, within the stipulated period, the person who was an association member operating or controlling an unmanned aircraft system of the fact that their membership in the association has ceased;

- 9. operating an unmanned aircraft system in contravention of § 54o (5)(i), failing to have liability insurance for damages from the operation of an unmanned aircraft system with the minimum stipulated limit of insurance coverage or failing to have paid the insurance premium; or

- 10. in contravention of § 54o (6), failing to notify the Authority, within the stipulated period, of a change in the fact on the basis of which the association's authorization was granted, or failing to submit documents proving this change;

- c) as a member of an authorized association:

- 1. in contravention of § 54o (4), operating or controlling an unmanned aircraft system; or

- 2. operating an unmanned aircraft system in contravention of § 54p (2), failing to have liability insurance for damages from the operation of an unmanned aircraft system with the minimum stipulated limit of insurance coverage or failing to have paid the insurance premium;

- d) as a common information service provider or a controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service provider pursuant to a directly applicable European Union regulation governing controlled unmanned aircraft system airspace^40), in contravention of § 54r (2) or (3), failing to surrender, within the stipulated period, the certificate proving authorization to provide a common information service or a controlled unmanned aircraft system traffic service; or

- e) as an air traffic service provider, failing to provide operational information pursuant to a directly applicable European Union regulation governing requirements for air traffic management service providers^44).

(4) For an administrative offense, a fine may be imposed:

- a) up to 50,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1(c) point 5 or (d), paragraph 2(d) point 2, or paragraph 3(a) point 1, 2 or 7, (b) point 8 or (d);

- b) up to 75,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1(b) point 2 or 5 or (c) point 3, 4 or 8, or paragraph 3(a) point 6 or (b) point 10;

- c) up to 100,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1(a), (b) point 1, 3 or 4 or (c) point 1, 2, 6 or 7, paragraph 2(c) point 2 or (d) point 1 or 3, or paragraph 3(a) point 3, 4 or 5, (b) point 2 to 5 or 9 or (c);

- d) up to 500,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 3(b) point 1, 6 or 7;

- e) up to 3,000,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 1(b) point 6 or paragraph 2(b) or (c) point 1 or paragraph 3(e); or

- f) from 100,000 CZK to 5,000,000 CZK, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 2(a).

(5) For an administrative offense, a prohibition of activity for up to 2 years may be imposed, if it is an administrative offense according to paragraph 2(a).

